# kube-saver improvements

Remaining work to make kube-saver production-ready and star-worthy.
Items 1-20 are done — README, docs/, screenshots, comparison, and trust content shipped.

---

## A. Trust & verification (high-impact, currently unproven)

- [ ] **A1.** Verify the app works the same from source install, wheel install, and Docker image install on a clean machine.
- [ ] **A2.** Test against at least one local cluster, one managed cloud cluster, and one restricted RBAC environment before each release.
- [ ] **A3.** Publish a support matrix: Kubernetes versions, Python versions, Linux distros, container runtimes, CPU architectures.
- [ ] **A4.** Add a `kube-saver doctor` command that checks kubeconfig, context, cluster connectivity, and required permissions.
- [ ] **A5.** Run smoke tests in CI: install from the built wheel, run basic commands, and verify the Docker image generates at least one real report.

## B. RBAC & production safety

- [ ] **B1.** Publish the minimum required Kubernetes RBAC permissions for read-only production usage.
- [ ] **B2.** Provide ready-to-apply sample RBAC manifests for namespace-scoped and cluster-scoped deployments.
- [ ] **B3.** Document how to run kube-saver inside a container with mounted kubeconfig and in-cluster auth.
- [ ] **B4.** Make all cluster connection failures return clear, stable exit codes for automation.
- [ ] **B5.** Ensure every CLI command fails fast with a useful message when kubeconfig or context is invalid.
- [ ] **B6.** Add namespace-level and workload-level policy exclusions in config (e.g. protect stateful, latency-sensitive, or manually tuned workloads).
- [ ] **B7.** Keep the HTTP API bound to loopback by default and clearly warn when it is exposed on the network.

## C. Reliability & error handling

- [ ] **C1.** Add explicit timeout settings for Kubernetes API calls and document safe production defaults.
- [ ] **C2.** Add bounded retry behavior for transient Kubernetes API failures and log when retries happen.
- [ ] **C3.** Ensure retries never hide final failures or make slow clusters appear healthy.
- [ ] **C4.** Verify the app behaves safely when metrics are stale, delayed, or missing for part of the cluster.
- [ ] **C5.** Review exception handling so failures are surfaced clearly instead of being swallowed.

## D. Performance & scaling

- [ ] **D1.** Benchmark data collection speed on clusters with many namespaces, pods, and nodes.
- [ ] **D2.** Profile memory usage for large-cluster scans and reduce unnecessary object retention.
- [ ] **D3.** Add throttling or batching if API requests become too expensive on large clusters.
- [ ] **D4.** Add a safe cache strategy only where it improves performance without hiding fresh cluster state.
- [ ] **D5.** Make cache behavior visible so users know when they are seeing cached versus freshly collected data.

## E. Observability & logging

- [ ] **E1.** Add structured logging for production automation and log aggregation systems.
- [ ] **E2.** Add configurable log levels for quiet CI usage and detailed troubleshooting.
- [ ] **E3.** Ensure logs never print secrets, tokens, kubeconfig contents, or sensitive cluster metadata.
- [ ] **E4.** Add redaction rules for all diagnostics, config dumps, and crash output.
- [ ] **E5.** Add a command to print the effective merged configuration with secrets redacted.

## F. Output stability & compatibility

- [ ] **F1.** Define compatibility expectations for JSON and HTTP response shapes before external consumers depend on them.
- [ ] **F2.** Make generated HTML reports stable, readable, and self-contained across browsers and offline use.
- [ ] **F3.** Add snapshot or golden tests for HTML, JSON, Markdown, and Prometheus output formats.
- [ ] **F4.** Verify reports remain readable with long namespace names, many workloads, and non-English text.
- [ ] **F5.** Add explanation sections in reports for how waste, cost, and recommendations are calculated.
- [ ] **F6.** Record why each recommendation was produced so operators can review and trust it.

## G. Testing

- [ ] **G1.** Add tests for empty clusters, large clusters, overloaded clusters, and partially reachable clusters.
- [ ] **G2.** Add tests for malformed Kubernetes resource quantities and unexpected object shapes from APIs.
- [ ] **G3.** Test recommendation behavior against real workload patterns instead of only synthetic examples.
- [ ] **G4.** Add regression tests for every production bug fix so old problems do not reappear.

## H. CI/CD & supply chain

- [ ] **H1.** Maintain strict lint, typing, test, build, and Docker verification in CI for every release.
- [ ] **H2.** Add vulnerability scanning for Python dependencies and container images in CI.
- [ ] **H3.** Generate SBOMs for release artifacts and Docker images.
- [ ] **H4.** Publish image digests in release notes so operators can deploy immutable references.
- [ ] **H5.** Add OCI labels for source repository, version, revision, and license to container images.
- [ ] **H6.** Track Docker image size over time and prevent accidental bloat.
- [ ] **H7.** Test Docker images on clean hosts without local repo state or development tools.
- [ ] **H8.** Define a release checklist covering version bump, verification, tagging, rollback, and post-release validation.

## I. Repository governance

- [ ] **I1.** Add branch protection and required review rules for main.
- [ ] **I2.** Require passing status checks before merge.
- [ ] **I3.** Add CODEOWNERS for critical areas (CI, Docker, config, collectors, release).
- [ ] **I4.** Add issue templates for bugs, incidents, and production environment problems.
- [ ] **I5.** Add pull request templates that require verification details and release impact notes.
- [ ] **I6.** Add a security policy and private reporting path for sensitive issues.
- [ ] **I7.** Set GitHub repo topics, description, and social preview image for discoverability.

## J. TUI & UX

- [ ] **J1.** Improve TUI accessibility, color contrast, and resilience on smaller terminals.
- [ ] **J2.** Make TUI refresh state, stale data state, and loading state more obvious to operators.
- [ ] **J3.** Add protections so malformed or partial data cannot crash the TUI.
- [ ] **J4.** Add non-interactive summary output modes for automation.
- [ ] **J5.** Standardize warning and error wording across TUI, CLI, server mode, and exported outputs.

